xpectations for upper-middle-class women in Toronto in the 1940s and 1950s, which included post-secondary education, marriage, and motherhood. While raising a family and supporting her husband’s academic career, she continued her formal education through part-time study and gradually began a journey tailored to herself as an individual. In her forties, she embarked on her own academic career, rising through the ranks to become a tenured full professor and chair of the department of occupational therapy in the Faculty of Medicine at the University of Toronto. In There Was a Time for Everything, Friedland reflects on her life and the fact that over time she managed to "have it all" – just not all at once.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2023) 0aJewish womenzOntariozTorontovBiography. 0aWomen college teacherszOntariozTorontovBiography. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Personal Memoirs.2bisacsh  aCanadian women’s history.  aFaculty of Medicine.  aJewish family life.  aUniversity of Toronto.  aautobiography.  alife stories.  amemoir.  amid-twentieth century Toronto.  aoccupational therapy.  awomen in academia.  awomen.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311079736740uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148754697740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487546977423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781487546977/original  a978-3-11-079736-7  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK